<subSubSection lastPageId="92" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="92" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
Shrubs to small trees 1-5 m tall with subtetragonal stems that become terete and that are densely beset with simple roughened to dendritic trichomes near the tips, a small layer of inconspicuous underdeveloped dendritic trichomes also present, glabrescent to glabrous with age; the nodal line present, covered or not by indument on young branches. Leaves of a pair equal to somewhat unequal in length. Petiole 0.5-3.5 cm, adaxially pubescent like the stem apices. Leaf blade 4-13 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-5 cm, 3-nerved, oblong, linear to elliptic or ovate to obovate, the base acute to rounded, the apex rounded to acute or acuminate, the margin entire, the adaxial surface glabrous, the abaxial surface essentially glabrous, sometimes with short stipitate and sessile stellate 
<pageBreakToken pageId="92" pageNumber="93" start="start">trichomes</pageBreakToken>
on the mid vein and some secondary veins and inconspicuously glandular puncticulate throughout. Inflorescence a terminal panicle 3-8.5 cm long branched above the base, accessory branches apparently absent, bracts and bracteoles 0.5-2 mm, subulate, deciduous. Pedicel 7-13 mm. Flowers 5-7 merous, calyptrate. Floral buds 11-20 mm long, ovoid, the base obtuse to rounded, the apex acute and mucronate, not constricted, the hypanthium 6-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-7 mm, smooth and glabrous. Petals 6-17 mm long, white. Stamens 11-18, 6-8 mm long, the filaments 3.4-4.4 mm long, white, lacking a conspicuous geniculation, anthers 3-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.8-1 mm, subulate, recurved at the tip, yellow, somewhat laterally compressed, the pore ca. 0.1 mm wide, terminal. Ovary 5-7 locular, inferior, apically glabrous and forming a collar around the style base. Style ca. 8-9 mm, straight to slightly bent at the tip, vertical distance from the anther to the stigma -0-1 mm, horizontal distance absent, the stigma truncate, ca. 04-0.5 mm wide. Berry ca. 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
10 mm, red at first but turning purple black with maturity. Seeds ca 0.8 mm, pyramidal, smooth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="94" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
<pageBreakToken pageId="93" pageNumber="94" start="start">Distribution</pageBreakToken>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 100" captionStartId="F100" captionText="Figure 100. Distribution of Conostegia pyxidata." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure100" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96458" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">100</figureCitation>
). Endemic to Jamaica, 200-1100 m in elevation.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973840" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure100" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96458" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" start="Figure 100" startId="F100">
<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Figure 100.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Proctor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pyxidata" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyxidata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia pyxidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
discusses at length that 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Proctor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pyxidata" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyxidata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia pyxidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia balbisiana" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="balbisiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia balbisiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia procera" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia procera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He chose to maintain the species on a 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“borderline”">&quot;borderline&quot;</normalizedToken>
decision and gave three reasons for keeping the three taxa as distinct: 1) some morphological differences in a small area; 2) the disjunct range of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia balbisiana" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="balbisiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia balbisiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and 3) differences in flowering time between the more similar species 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia procera" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia procera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Proctor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pyxidata" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyxidata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia pyxidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia balbisiana" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="balbisiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia balbisiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
overlapping somewhat in flowering time with the other two species, but having larger flowers with different stamen morphology. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
argued that these morphological and phenological differences suggested the presence of biological isolation and a diverging lineage. For the time being I have chosen to follow 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Schnell’s">Schnell's</normalizedToken>
reasoning for recognizing three taxa. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
also suggested the possibility of introgression from 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Naudin" authorityYear="1850" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia rufescens" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The type of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Proctor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia subprocera" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subprocera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia subprocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not studied but 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
cited this name as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Proctor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia pyxidata" order="Myrtales" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyxidata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Conostegia pyxidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
